===Etymology 1===
[[Image:Biber-drawing.jpg|thumb|Beavers]]
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bever|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|beofor||beaver|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*bebruz||beaver}} (compare Dutch {{term|bever|lang=nl}}, French {{term|bièvre|lang=fr}}, German {{term|Biber|lang=de}}, dialectal Swedish {{term|bjur|lang=sv}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰébʰrus||beaver}} (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|befer|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|fiber|lang=la}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|bẽbras|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|бобр||tr=bobr|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|ae|-}} {{term|||tr=bawra|lang=ae}}, {{term|||tr=bawri|lang=ae}} {{rfscript|ae}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|बभ्रु||tr=bábhru|mongoose; ichneumon|lang=sa}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰreu-||shining, brown}}. Related to [[brown]] and [[bear]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun|s|beaver}}

# An [[aquatic]] [[rodent]] of the genus ''[[Castor]]'', having a wide, flat tail and webbed feet.
# A hat, of various shape, made from a felted beaver fur (or later of silk), fashionable in Europe between 1550 and 1850
# {{non-gloss definition|A possibly different "beaver hat" is mentioned by Chaucer in both ''Canterbury Tales'' and ''Testament of Creeside'', and indeed much earlier in Normandy ''Chronicle of the Abbey of St Wandrille'' refers to a hat given before 833 as "quem vulgaris Bevurum".}}<ref>Notes and Queries Vol. 1 (21) 23 March 1850 Page 338</ref>
#* Prescott
#*: a brown '''beaver''' slouched over his eyes
# {{context|coarse|slang|lang=en}} The [[pubic hair]] and/or [[vulva]] of a woman.
# The [[fur]] of the beaver.
# Beaver cloth, a heavy felted woollen cloth, used chiefly for making overcoats.

